Regardless of what dictionaries say, when a company changes a phrase like this, they are doing it for a reason.  In this case, they want to start to educate their target audience on what they consider an expansion or extension is.<br>
<br>
The mere fact they called it an extension tells you it will most likely have a different focus than any previous expansion.  That's pretty well the point of changing the term used.<br>
<br>
Whether or not it is a good thing, or indeed if people agree with it, is actually not relevent (thats a different part of marketing, making people see value in something).<br>
<br>
oh, and if you do want to use a dictionary, you should expand down a level.  so for &quot;Extention (the act of extending)&quot; you define extending, and for &quot;Expansion (making larger, expanding)&quot; you define expanding.  Because at the moment the definitions are to similar to the word being looked up (there is a term for that, but it escapes me at the moment).<br>
<br>
<br>
As a side note, the top of the spells patch says &quot;these may change&quot;.  So the legal people are pretty well involved as well.  I can't believe that 3 days before it goes live that they  haven't locked the spells in.  (err, actually, I can).<br>
<br>
<br>
Anyone want to lay odds on another &quot;online extension&quot; in 6 months?<br>
<br>
<br>
just my views, others may vary.  <br>
